Mrs. Muinat Lawal-Akapo, mother of Oba Omogbolahan Lawal, the Oniru of Iru Kingdom in Lagos, is dead. She was 85. In a statement, the monarch said his octogenarian mother died yesterday. “In total submission to the will of Almighty Allah, Oba  Omogbolahan Lawal (Abisogun II), Oniru of Iru Kingdom, the entire Abisogun- Oniru royal family, Ajasa , Sokun (Onilegbale) Royal House of Lagos, Olorogun Atebo and Olorogun Agan Chieftaincy Family of Lagos  and the Lawal-Akapo and Ojora families announce the death of our mother, Olori Muinat Olabisi Abeni Ajasa  Lawal-Akapo.”   Association condemns attack on activist     Senator Abiru greets lawmaker at 50     We’re desperate to fix Nigeria, says party   Lagos State Cooperative College (LASCOCO) is set to graduate 104 students under its professional diploma programme. The Provost, Mr. Akorede Ojomu, who made this known yesterday at a news briefing to herald the maiden convocation and graduation of professional diploma students, said honorary award of fellowship would be given to five persons who had been instrumental to the development of the college, at the event holding on April 7. Those to be conferred with the award are the former Commissioner for Agriculture and Cooperatives and Oniru of Iruland, Oba Lawal, ex-Commissioner for Commerce, Industry and Cooperatives Mrs. Olayinka Oladunjoye, retired permanent secretaries Mr. Wale Raji, Dr. Yaqub Olajide Bashorun and Mr. Lekan Akodu. He said the title of convocation lecture is: “Concern for the 21st Century economy: what roles do cooperatives have to play in the transition to a sustainable economy”. It will be delivered by the Chief Executive Officer and Principal of the United Kingdom Cooperative College, Mr. Neil Calvert.